# 52_actions_smoke — first move on Tier 2 action wrappers (s254 m2).
# Validates the `curvz::Action` plumbing landed at s254 m2 by
# exercising the five wrap-now win.* actions migrated to scripted
# actions: undo / redo / select-all / deselect-all / zoom-fit.
#
# **Conservative-shape smoke.** This is a verb-presence + invocation-
# no-throw smoke, not a full observable-confirmation smoke. The five
# m1 first-batch actions have NO scriptable observables today —
# undo/redo affect the command history (no Scriptable property
# exposes its depth), select-all/deselect-all affect canvas selection
# (no Scriptable property exposes selection count), and zoom-fit
# affects the canvas zoom (no Scriptable property exposes zoom).
# Adding those properties is m3+ territory; m2's smoke proves the
# wrapper-side dispatch lands and the actions are addressable from
# script. Convergent-evidence acceptance: trace shows the five
# invocations land cleanly (no `error invoke threw:` lines), plus
# Scott's visual confirmation that menu Edit ▸ Undo / Redo / Select
# All / Deselect All and View ▸ Zoom to Fit still behave identically
# to before (the wrapper is structurally invariant — same callback
# chain runs on script-driven invoke as on menu click).
#
# ── What this smoke exercises ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Six observables across the wrapper-side surface:
#
#   Phase 1: `list` — confirm `win` appears in the registered-
#            Scriptables enumeration. Operator-visual; the trace
#            should include a line `  win  (...)` somewhere in the
#            list output. Negative case: `win` missing means the
#            ActionGroupScriptable's ctor never ran or never reached
#            the registry, and m2 is broken at the foundation.
#
#   Phases 2-6: each of the five wrap-now verbs invoked once.
#            Operator-visual on each `ok` echo. Negative case: any
#            `error invoke threw:` line means the verb isn't in
#            m_actions (helper didn't register), the verb threw at
#            invocation (callback couldn't be adapted), or the
#            wrapper-side mask refused (which would be a mask-setup
#            bug — these are all default Scripter | TestRunner).
#
#            Each invoke also fires the underlying Gio action's
#            callback. Side effects ARE present (the canvas does
#            do undo / redo / select-all / etc.) — but they're not
#            assertable from script today. Scott's visual report is
#            the second channel.
#
# Phases 7-8: refusal coverage. Confirms the wrapper refuses unknown
#            verbs and refuses argument-bearing invocations of
#            parameterless verbs (per the invoke()-body contract).
#            Both are `error invoke threw:` lines; operator-visual
#            on the refusal text.
#
# ── Caller context ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke runs through ScripterWindow's listener, m_context =
# RunContext::Scripter. All five m1 first-batch verbs declare their
# mask as Scripter | TestRunner per the wrap-now posture (matches the
# m5b proj.save / export.svg / export.png / export.theme convention).
# Macro is OUT — the m1 first batch is observable-mutating but not
# observable-recordable in any safe way today. The wrap-now actions
# that DO record cleanly (`undo` / `redo` would replay fine in a
# macro) are excluded from Macro on the same posture as proj.save:
# the canon's "default is widest reasonable" rule reads "Scripter +
# TestRunner" as the wrap-now reasonable default; promoting verbs to
# Macro happens when a specific recording use case names the need.
#
# This is the FIRST consumer of context_mask() with a per-verb
# mask catalogue inside a single Scriptable (the registry-promotion
# clock counter — see LEDGER's Tier 4 row — gets one tick per
# Scriptable, not per verb; ActionGroupScriptable adds the eighth
# consumer to that clock). The wrap-now batch lands five verbs all
# at the same mask, but the wrapper accepts per-verb declaration
# from the start so stricter masks (e.g. for `clear` once it lands)
# can override the default without surgery.
#
# ── Test isolation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke MUTATES canvas state via undo / redo / select-all /
# deselect-all / zoom-fit. The mutations are:
#
#   - `win undo` — pops one entry off the command history if the
#                  stack is non-empty. **No-op if empty.** That's
#                  the safe shape for the smoke — running on an
#                  empty history does nothing observable and doesn't
#                  throw.
#   - `win redo` — pushes the last undone entry back on if any. No-op
#                  if the undo stack is at its head. Also safe-empty.
#   - `win select-all` — selects every visible object in the active
#                  layer. Idempotent.
#   - `win deselect-all` — clears selection. Idempotent.
#   - `win zoom-fit` — pans + zooms canvas to fit all objects. Idempotent
#                  on identical content.
#
# After the smoke runs:
#   - Command history is at the same position (undo+redo cancel out).
#   - Selection is empty (final deselect-all).
#   - Canvas zoom is whatever zoom-fit produced for the doc — likely
#     different from where the user had it. Scott will need to ⌘0 /
#     zoom-reset manually if this is disruptive.
#
# No project content is added, removed, or edited. Safe to run
# repeatedly.
#
# ── Precondition reminders ────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke assumes:
#   1. Curvz is running with at least one project + one document
#      open (every smoke assumes this).
#   2. The active doc has at least one object visible (so select-all
#      / zoom-fit have something to act on; the actions themselves
#      don't refuse on empty docs, but the visual confirmation channel
#      is more legible with content).
#
# Both preconditions are the standard "any session with anything on
# screen" baseline — same as smokes 26 / 41 / 49 / 51.

#[sub] === Phase 1: registry-presence — `win` Scriptable is registered ===

#[sub] `list` enumerates every registered Scriptable. The output
#[sub] should include a `win` line — the ActionGroupScriptable that
#[sub] m_action_group_scriptable was constructed as in MainWindow's
#[sub] ctor, BEFORE setup_menu() ran. If `win` is missing here, the
#[sub] ctor's construction step never landed or the registration
#[sub] silently failed; nothing below can pass.

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: undo verb is addressable ===

#[sub] First wrapped verb. Invoke; no error means the helper
#[sub] correctly registered the action and the wrapper's invoke()
#[sub] resolved the verb name and called activate() on the
#[sub] underlying SimpleAction. If the command history is empty,
#[sub] this is a clean no-op at the canvas layer.
#[sub]
#[sub] Negative case: `error invoke threw: win undo: unknown verb`
#[sub] means register_action() never landed for this verb.

win undo

#[sub] === Phase 3: redo verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Sibling to undo. Symmetric registration test.

win redo

#[sub] === Phase 4: select-all verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Third wrapped verb. Calls m_canvas.select_all(); visual
#[sub] confirmation: all objects in active layer should select.

win select-all

#[sub] === Phase 5: deselect-all verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Fourth wrapped verb. Calls m_canvas.clear_selection(); visual
#[sub] confirmation: selection clears. Leaves the canvas in a clean
#[sub] selection-empty state for the final zoom-fit.

win deselect-all

#[sub] === Phase 6: zoom-fit verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Fifth and final wrapped verb. Calls m_canvas.zoom_to_all_objects();
#[sub] visual confirmation: canvas reframes to fit content. This is
#[sub] the most visually-obvious of the five — Scott's eyes-channel
#[sub] confirmation is most reliable on this one.

win zoom-fit

#[sub] === Phase 7: unknown-verb refusal ===

#[sub] The wrapper refuses verbs that aren't in m_actions. The five
#[sub] migrated verbs are present; the other 44 wrap-now and 25 don't-
#[sub] wrap actions are NOT — they're either still in the un-migrated
#[sub] Gio-only state (the 44 remaining wrap-now, future milestones)
#[sub] or decided-not-deferred and never going to be wrapped (the
#[sub] don't-wrap buckets).
#[sub]
#[sub] `win quit` is a bucket-C action (future `app.quit` singleton);
#[sub] it's a clean test of the unknown-verb refusal because it's a
#[sub] real Gio action (so the menu still works) but NOT in the
#[sub] wrapper's verb surface. The refusal message names the verb
#[sub] and points the script author at the audit doc.

win quit

#[sub] === Phase 8: extra-argument refusal ===

#[sub] All five m1 first-batch verbs are parameterless. Passing an
#[sub] argument should refuse — silently dropping args would mask
#[sub] scripts that think they're parameterising a verb that doesn't
#[sub] accept parameters.

win undo "argument"

#[sub] === Predicted observables ───────────────────────────────────────────

